    {
      "title": "Show HN: OSS Agent I built topped the TerminalBench on Gemini-3-flash-preview",
      "url": "https://github.com/dirac-run/dirac",
      "source": "rss",
      "popularity": 0,
      "popularity_type": "none",
      "author": "",
      "created_at": "2026-04-30T08:13:14+08:00",
      "updated_at": "2026-04-30T08:13:14+08:00",
      "language": "N/A",
      "topics": [],
      "description": "<p>Scored 65.2% vs google's official 47.8%, and the existing top closed source model Junie CLI's 64.3%.<p>Since there are a lot of reports of deliberate cheating on TerminalBench 2.0 lately (<a href=\"https://debugml.github.io/cheating-agents/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://debugml.github.io/cheating-agents/</a>), I would like to also clarify a few things<p>1. Absolutely no {agents/skills}.md files were inserted at any point. No cheating mechanisms whatsoever<p>2. The cli agent was run in leaderboard compliant way (no modification of resources or timeouts)<p>3. The full terminal bench run was done using the fully open source version of the agent, no difference between what is on github and what was run.<p>I was originally going to wait for it to land on the leaderboard, but it has been 8 days and the maintainers do not respond unfortunately (there is a large backlog of the pull requests on their HF) so I decided to post anyways.<p>HF PR: <a href=\"https://huggingface.co/datasets/harborframework/terminal-bench-2-leaderboard/discussions/145\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://huggingface.co/datasets/harborframework/terminal-ben...</a><p>It is astounding how much the harness matters, based on this and other experiments I have done.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47920787\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47920787</a></p>\n<p>Points: 385</p>\n<p># Comments: 145</p>",
      "readme": "",
      "summary": "",
      "collected_at": "2026-04-30T08:13:14+08:00"
    },
